Title:
PE-XRay (PE-XRay-EDR)

Type:
GitHub Tool

Short Summary (4–8 sentences max):
PE-XRay is a lightweight static analyzer for Windows PE files (.exe/.dll) that uses heuristic scoring rather than signature matching to highlight suspicious traits. It targets common malware/packer/protector indicators by inspecting PE structure, section properties, imports, entropy, and embedded strings. The tool flags anomalies such as malformed headers, unusual entry points, RWX (write+execute) sections, high entropy regions suggestive of packing/encryption, and risky WinAPI imports (e.g., CreateRemoteThread, SetWindowsHookExW). It provides both a GUI (IUP) and a CLI build, aimed at quickly triaging binaries and surfacing “evidence” for analyst decision-making. Useful for malware analysts, incident responders, and red teamers validating payload OPSEC against static heuristics.

Technical Focus:
- PE header/section parsing and structural anomaly detection
- Heuristic-based risk scoring engine
- Entropy analysis (global + sliding-window)
- Import table inspection for suspicious WinAPI usage
- String extraction/intelligence (commands, URLs, tooling artifacts)

Use Cases:
- Rapid triage of unknown executables and DLLs during investigations
- Identifying packed/encrypted binaries via entropy and section traits
- Spotting injection/persistence-related API imports in samples
- Pre-deployment OPSEC checks of red team payloads against static heuristics
- Hunting for malformed/weaponized PE structures in malware collections

Keywords:
Portable Executable, PE parsing, static analysis, heuristic detection, entropy scanning, sliding-window entropy, packer detection, import table analysis, WinAPI, CreateRemoteThread, SetWindowsHookExW, RWX sections, section flags, entry point anomalies, malformed headers, string extraction, malware triage, Windows executables, MinGW-w64, IUP GUI